ce:section.ce:para:
O-and S-doped CxNy QDs were synthesized by hydrothermal process using different ratios of cysteine and maleic acid at 150 °C. In a typical synthesis, 363.4 mg (3.0 mmol) of cysteine and 58.0 mg (0.5 mmol) of maleic acid (6:1 molar ratio) were mixed together and grounded into fine powder with the help of agate mortar pestle. This mixed sample was now placed into hydrothermal bomb and heated at 150 °C for 90 min. After that, hydrothermal bomb was cooled to room temperature and brownish char was recovered by dispersing in 100 mL of ultrapure water (see inset of Fig. 1
                        ). Thereafter, it was centrifuged into several parts at 4000 rpm for 5 min to remove larger non-fluorescent particles, the further purification was carried out by dialyzing it against ultrapure water in dialysis membrane (MW = 10 k Da) for 48 h. This obtained O- and S-doped CxNy suspension was labeled as CM61 and kept for further characterization purpose. Fig. 1 summarizes the strategy for synthesis of QDs. Similar procedures were adopted for synthesis of CM31, CM91 and CM121 by varying the molar ratios of cysteine and maleic acid in 3:1, 9:1 and 12:1 respectively. Quantum yields of all these as-prepared O- and S-doped CxNy QDs are calculated (Table 1
                         and SI Eq. (1)) using quinine sulphate (QY = 54.0% in 0.1 M H2SO4) as standard. CM61 has highest quantum yield of 20.08% among others due to homogeneous surface organization. Therefore, this optimized fractional product is extended for other experimentations (as discussed later) and sensing applications; while rest samples were discarded. A comparison of quantum yield of O- and S-doped CxNy QDs (CM61) with others reported C-dots and carbon nitride dots has been provided in Supporting information (Table S1).
